title: XTC Support V1
body:
This is a fairly isolated change. I really only had to do two things.

1.  Make all unit test faster to reduce XTC costs (all tests now finish sub second'ish).
2. Update the UI checks in Sensus.Tests.Cloud to work with our existing test runner.

Once you pull this change you should be able to run the Sensus.Tests.Cloud locally. It'll start up both the iOS and Android app and then perform a UI check to make sure no tests break. If you look at the code, you can see this is exactly how it works in XTC as well except it only runs either iOS or Android and not both simultaneously.

Oh, I also had to comment out tests we don't want to run rather than marking them as explicit. That's because our current test runners show un-run tests as failures and it was really hard to handle that with UI queries for a number of reasons.

body:
GitHub Works now :). Closes #275. 

This test is a lot better. We now determine if a deadlock happened by checking to see if all expected items are added to the test array. If they aren't then we assume the synchronize action didn't finish which would be indicative of a deadlock.

title: A shot in the dark based on the exceptions in Insights
body:
We have some users reporting that they don't receive surveys. [These](https://insights.xamarin.com/app/Sensus-Production/issues/1219) exceptions in Insights appear to be related. We thought this was all related to the bands because the last log entry on phones with this issue is usually related to the bands. However, upon further investigation, it appears there is a confounding variable behind the bands (i.e. the notifications that bring the Sensus into the foreground). 

With all that said, I have no idea why this code would only break some phones rather than all iPhones. Still this seems to be the most likely cause to me given the exception message in Insight. Without an exact line number it is hard to say though.

Should close #258

title: Concurrent With Unit Tests
body:
Dr. Gerber,

I noticed your UI thread synchronization code. I factored that code out into an interface I call IConcurrent.

Because race conditions can be so tricky I really wanted Unit Tests to make sure it worked as expected.

After reading, experimenting and testing, I finally found an architecture that allows us to write tests for both code that doesn't require an emulator and code that does. I added a bunch of new projects but each one has a purpose that I'm happy to explain.

I wanted to go ahead and get the pull request in the pipe because the changes touched a whole bunch of files and I'm worried about merge conflicts if we wait too long on this one.

Thanks,

Mark

title: Final Bundle of VS Changes
body:
Prof. Gerber,

Here are a few final changes to get sensus fully integrated into the Microsoft's VS IDE.

The big thing was I had the wrong build configuration so I was building all the projects. This meant Sensus.UiTest was building, and it didn't have up to date packages with the other projects. I now have the build configuration set correctly on my windows machine. However, since I'd already gotten the project up to date I went ahead and committed the package changes.

The other change in this bundle was explicitly setting the memory available for the JRE. I guess the default JRE settings on Windows are different from Mac because out of the box I hit an OME when spinning up the Android emulator. I explicitly set the memory reservation to 1 GB and no longer have any issues.

I thought I'd just go ahead and push these up by themselves so we can merge them by themselves. That way, in the future, when I'm doing actual changes the diffs will look cleaner and won't include a bunch of extra stuff.
